            <div id="id1" style="height: 43px; left: 20px; position: absolute; top: 20px; width: 515px; z-index: 1; " class="style_SkipStroke shape-with-text">
              <div class="text-content Normal_External_515_43" style="padding: 0px; ">
                <div class="Normal">
                  <p style="padding-bottom: 0pt; padding-top: 0pt; " class="Header">Autocallable - 2</p>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div style="margin-left: 0px; position: relative; width: 1000px; z-index: 5; " id="body_layer">
            <div style="height: 0px; line-height: 0px; " class="bumper"> </div>
            <div id="id2" style="height: 248px; left: 15px; position: absolute; top: 16px; width: 957px; z-index: 1; " class="style_SkipStroke_1 shape-with-text">
              <div class="text-content graphic_textbox_layout_style_default_External_957_248" style="padding: 0px; ">
                <div class="graphic_textbox_layout_style_default">
                  <p style="padding-top: 0pt; " class="paragraph_style">A structured product market has a basic flaw that you can’t copyright any product. If you issue an exotic another bank might easily replicate that product and if the product is popular it will be replicated by number of banks. This is of course good for the investor as it results in highly competitive pricing but for a trader it sometimes becomes a nightmare.<br /></p>
                  <p class="paragraph_style"><br /></p>
                  <p style="padding-bottom: 0pt; " class="paragraph_style_1">Let us consider the hypothetical example of an autocallable issued today with autocall dates at 9-Sept-2012, 9-Jan-2013, 9-May-2013, 9-Sept-2013, 9-Jan-2014. Other banks might have priced a similar product with autocall dates close to september month. This is not a vague assumption as there is a huge market of autocallables and a number of them have close autocall dates. Take an emerging market - let’s assume NIFTY Index (nseindia.com) where daily volume for a particular strike is around <span class="style">5 - 10 million contracts</span>. </p>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>
            


            <div id="id3" style="height: 334px; left: 15px; position: absolute; top: 272px; width: 951px; z-index: 1; " class="style_SkipStroke_1 shape-with-text">
              <div class="text-content graphic_textbox_layout_style_default_External_951_334" style="padding: 0px; ">
                <div class="graphic_textbox_layout_style_default">
                  <p style="padding-top: 0pt; " class="paragraph_style_2">Bucketing<br /></p>
                  <p class="paragraph_style_2"><br /></p>
                  <p class="paragraph_style">Vega bucketing in general splits the greeks into particular maturity bucket. For example you can calculate 1m vega risk by bumping the 1m maturity volatility for all strikes and calculating the vega. All other maturities are kept constant. As discussed in previous post, the trader is long vega above the barrier, so the hedges are short vega. As the underlying rallies - let’s say 15 days before the autocall date. <br /></p>
                  <p class="paragraph_style"><br /></p>
                  <ol>
                    <li style="line-height: 22px; padding-left: 19px; text-indent: -19px; " class="full-width" value="1">
                      <p style="text-indent: -19px; " class="paragraph_style_3"><span style="font-size: 18px; " class="Bullet">1.</span><span style="width: 6px; " class="inline-block"></span>Probability of autocall increases <br /></p>
                    </li>
                    <li style="line-height: 22px; padding-left: 19px; text-indent: -19px; " class="full-width" value="1">
                      <p style="text-indent: -19px; " class="paragraph_style_4"><span style="font-size: 18px; " class="Bullet">a)</span><span style="width: 4px; " class="inline-block"></span>Shorter maturity requires rebalancing<br /></p>
                    </li>
                    <li style="line-height: 22px; padding-left: 19px; text-indent: -19px; " class="full-width" value="2">
                      <p style="text-indent: -19px; " class="paragraph_style_4"><span style="font-size: 18px; " class="Bullet">b)</span><span style="width: 4px; " class="inline-block"></span>Longer dated vega hedges need to be bought back, and short dated vegas need to be sold<br /></p>
                    </li>
                  </ol>
                  <p class="paragraph_style"><br /></p>
                  <p class="paragraph_style">Due to a) and b) - The demand for upside calls increases<br /></p>
                  <p style="padding-bottom: 0pt; " class="paragraph_style">This is interesting if the total notional of autocalls in the market is 1000 million, </p>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>
            


            <div id="id4" style="height: 490px; left: 27px; position: absolute; top: 719px; width: 847px; z-index: 1; " class="style_SkipStroke_1 shape-with-text">
              <div class="text-content graphic_textbox_layout_style_default_External_847_490" style="padding: 0px; ">
                <div class="graphic_textbox_layout_style_default">
                  <p style="padding-top: 0pt; " class="paragraph_style">So hedging would require a total of 12.75 million contracts to be executed in a day, and the same number of short dated contracts for completing the rebalance. This is twice the size of daily Nifty volume. <br /></p>
                  <p class="paragraph_style"><br /></p>
                  <p class="paragraph_style">This buying as a whole will cause some directional affect on the index. For example in this case the put spreads need to be bought back and rolled to shorter maturity put spreads. Long dated put spreads buying might not affect the market that much, but shorting “short dated” put spreads might push the market further down. As explained there will be a huge demand for lower OTM strike puts. Sellers of those puts will hedge by shorting futures and hence push the market downward. <br /></p>
                  <p class="paragraph_style"><br /></p>
                  <ol>
                    <li style="line-height: 22px; padding-left: 19px; text-indent: -19px; " class="full-width" value="2">
                      <p style="text-indent: -19px; " class="paragraph_style_5"><span style="font-size: 18px; " class="Bullet">2.</span><span style="width: 6px; " class="inline-block"></span>Market rallies downwards<br /></p>
                    </li>
                    <li style="line-height: 22px; padding-left: 19px; text-indent: -19px; " class="full-width" value="1">
                      <p style="text-indent: -19px; " class="paragraph_style_6"><span style="font-size: 18px; " class="Bullet">a)</span><span style="width: 4px; " class="inline-block"></span>Probability of knock in put being triggered increases<br /></p>
                    </li>
                    <li style="line-height: 22px; padding-left: 19px; text-indent: -19px; " class="full-width" value="2">
                      <p style="text-indent: -19px; " class="paragraph_style_6"><span style="font-size: 18px; " class="Bullet">b)</span><span style="width: 4px; " class="inline-block"></span>Traders will want to sell downside puts in advance to hedge<br /></p>
                    </li>
                  </ol>
                  <p class="paragraph_style"><br /></p>
                  <p class="paragraph_style">The one’s who bought the puts will hedge the delta by buying stock, hence pushing the market upward. Combined affect can lead to a crash, coz you have multiple participants hedging exactly the same thing.<br /></p>
                  <p class="paragraph_style"><br /></p>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>
            


